).avif" loading=3D"lazy" alt=3D"how to calculate sample size for unknown po=
pulation"></div></figure><p>Here=E2=80=99s how the calculations work out fo=
r our voice recognition technology example in an office of 500 people, with=
 a 95% confidence level and 5% margin of error:</p><figure class=3D"w-richt=
ext-align-center w-richtext-figure-type-image"><div><img src=3D"https://cdn=
.prod.website-files.com/65d64f3968c4b864c79e9dfd/66a2b0cd4701f2f43676f4ca_6=
6a2b07783ff6a15e3b8d989_Blog-Inline-how-to-calculate-sample-size-3.avif" lo=
ading=3D"lazy" alt=3D"How is sample size determined"></div></figure><p>Ther=
e you have it! 197 respondents are needed.</p><p>You can tweak some things =
if that number is too big to swallow.</p><p>Try increasing your margin of e=
rror or decreasing your confidence level. This will reduce the number of re=
spondents necessary but, unfortunately, increase the chances of errors. Eve=
n so, understanding why trade-offs are necessary in sample size determinati=
on can help you make informed decisions.</p><h3>Summing Up Sample Size</h3>=
<p>Calculating sample size sounds complicated - but, utilizing an easy samp=
le size formula and even calculators are now available to make this tedious=
 part of market research faster!</p><p>Once you've determined your sample s=
ize, you're ready to create and distribute your sample market research surv=
ey. This can be done through methods like running a <a href=3D"https://reme=
sh.ai/should-you-use-online-focus-groups" target=3D"_blank">focus group </a=
>or even a <a href=3D"https://proprofs.com/c/customer-support/customer-sati=
sfaction-survey" target=3D"_blank">customer satisfaction survey</a>. Whatev=
er you decide, you now have the information needed to make decisions with c=
onfidence.</p><p>Want to whip your research skills into shape? Check out ou=
